1b) Generalize your code so you can make a plot of any X contiguous points (e.g. 2000 points starting at point 500), and produce an example plot of a set of data somethere in the middle of your array.

In [8]:
# t = given time axis, bkgd = created random background dependent on N, start = where we want to start slicing from, amount = how far we want to slice to. ex: 2000 points starting from 
# 500 will give us an x array from 500 to 2500. step is how much I want to go by. for the case in part c, i want step to be 100 since it will plot every 100th point
def slice_plot(t, bkgd, start, end, step):
    x = t[start:end: step]
    bkgd1 = bkgd[start:end: step]
    plt.scatter(x, bkgd1, s=5)
    if end != -1:
        plt.title('Data points from ' + str(start) + ' to ' + str(end))
    else:
        plt.title('Full Datastep with Step = ' + str(step))
    plt.xlabel('time')
    plt.ylabel('background')
slice_plot(t, bkgd, 500, 2500, 1)

2b) Clearly explain what is being plotted in your plot (e.g. what does each color mean?)

The plot shows the distribution of points and the colors describe the density of the points along the time axis. Looking at the color bar, the darker more purple/blue colors are where the points are not very dense and have a little amount of points where as the greener/yellower area has high density and so a lot of points are present. Looking at the plot above most points are hovering around the 10 background distribution mark and are evenly distributed with respect to time.
